        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We propose to image the distribution of the emission of the ethyl cyanide 
(C2H5CN) and methyl formate (HCOOCH3) toward the massive star-formation region 
NGC6334(I) in band 7 using the C34-3 configuration, resulting into an angular 
resolution of 0.4''. Also, the complex molecules we want to image seem to come 
from compact regions, since the source size is estimated to be less than 4'' 
based on i) our APEX observations and, ii) the Herschel/HIFI observations of 
this source (Zernickel et al. 2011). Therefore, spatial filtering is not likely
to adversely affect the observations.

Our ALMA-OT science goal will observe 3 basebands of 468.75 MHz and will 
therefore cover a bandwidth of 1.406 GHz. In addition, we set one baseband of 
937.5 MHz for continuum purpose due to the line richness of source. Also, 
from SMA continuum observations carried out at 1.3 mm by Hunter et al. (2006), 
we estimated that the continuum peak flux density should be about 0.22 Jy per 
beam. Likewise, we ask for spectral resolution of about 0.5 km/s in order to 
reduce the potential confusion.

We aim for a sensitivity of 2 mJy/beam which will give us, under nominal 
conditions (pwv of 1.262 mm) and according our model (which is based on the 
Herschel fits template spectra and on our APEX observations), a signal-to-noise 
ratio greater than 16-32 for the strongest lines, and S/N ratio of 3 for the 
less intense transitions. This requires a total observing time of  4.60 hours.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
