    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>One of the most important questions in the astrophysics of the interstellar medium is whether, how, when, and where organic molecules are formed. In the proposed observations we focus on the formations routes of complex N-bearing molecules, especially ethyl cyanide, C2H5CN. In particular, we address the role of the chemistry that occurs in hot cores, involving their production either by evaporation from ice mantles or by formation in gas phase. The recent Herschel detection of complex nitrogen-bearing species towards the Orion-KL star forming region have demonstrated that i) they are systematically tracing hotter gas than the oxygen-bearing organic molecules and, ii) some insights into the source thermal structure are apparent in the data. We propose to extend this study to the massive star forming region NGC6334(I) by using the ALMA observational capabilities in band 7. The data, along with laboratory experiments, will give insight into the formation mechanism of complex N-bearing species in star forming regions.Also, using the Herschel data fits that we have available, and that will be available to the community soon, we seek to merge the legacy of both Herschel and ALMA.</prp:abstract>
